adju&s;t them&s;elves wonderfully to their &s;tate,
and enable them to extract &s;atisfaction from
&s;ources that are totally unknown to others.
Were the great body of men fairly to com|pute
the hours which they pa&s;s in ea&s;e, and
even with &s;ome degree of plea&s;ure, they
would be found far to exceed the number
of tho&s;e which are &s;pent in ab&s;olute pain
either of body or mind.&mdash;But in order to
