&s;ubjection to the opinions of others.
<PB N="199" REF="206">
The di&s;tre&s;s which they produce, I admit,
is real; but its reality ari&s;es not from the
nature of things, but from that di&s;order of
imagination which a &s;mall mea&s;ure of re|flection
might rectify. In proof of this we
may ob&s;erve, that the per&s;ons who live mo&s;t
&s;imply, and follow the dictates of plain un|adulterated
nature, are mo&s;t exempted from
this cla&s;s of evils. It is among the higher
ranks of mankind that they chiefly abound;
where fanta&s;tic re&s;inements, &s;ickly delicacy,
and eager emulation, open a thou&s;and
&s;ources of vexation peculiar to them&s;elves.
Life cannot but prove vain to them who
