us by our own mi&s;conduct. Di&s;ea&s;es, po|verty,
di&s;appointment and &s;hame are far
from being, in every in&s;tance, the unavoid|able
doom of men. They are much more
frequently the offspring of their own mi&s;|guided
choice. Intemperance engenders
di&s;ea&s;e, &s;loth produces poverty, pride cre|ates
