of worldly felicity. Let us always remem|ber
where we are; from what cau&s;es the
human &s;tate has become &s;ubject to depre&s;|&s;ion;
and upon what accounts it mu&s;t re|main
under its pre&s;ent law. Such is the
infatuation of &s;elf-love, that though in the
general doctrine of the vanity of the world
<PB N="206" REF="213">
all men agree, yet almo&s;t every one flatters
him&s;elf that his own ca&s;e is to be an excep|tion
from the common rule. He re&s;ts on
expectations which he thinks can not fail
him; and though the pre&s;ent b$ not altoge|ther
according to his wi&s;h, yet with the
confidence of certain hope he anticipates
futurity. Hence the angui&s;h of di&s;appoint|ment
&s;ills the world; and evils, which are
of them&s;elves &s;ufficiently &s;evere, opppre&s;s with
