con&s;equence to real felicity, than all the pro|vi&s;ion
which we can make of the goods of
fortune. To this let us bend our chief at|tention.
Let us <HI>keep the heart with all di|ligence,
&s;eeing out of it are the i&s;&s;ues of life.</HI>
Let us account our mind the mo&s;t important
province which is committed to our care;
and if we cannot rule fortune, &s;tudy at lea&s;t
to rule our&s;elves. Let us propo&s;e for our
